          "body": "Verses 11-14 escalate from trapping to terror to bodily dissolution to violent death. 'All around terrors frighten him and harry him at every step' (18:11) — the very word *ballahah* (terror) that will become the title 'king of terrors' in verse 14. 'His skin is devoured by disease, the firstborn of death devours his limbs' (18:13) — a phrase unique in the Hebrew Bible. Commentators debate whether 'firstborn of death' is a demon figure from the ancient Near Eastern mythological background (cf. the pestilence-deity Mot in Ugaritic literature, which Peter Davids and others note as contextual background to Job's imagery), or simply a superlative: the most lethal force death possesses. Either way, the image is of consumption from without and within simultaneously. The climax of the section is the 'king of terrors' (18:14) — the personified sovereign of death before whom the wicked man is 'marched.' The word for marching (*tsaad*) is the same root used in verse 7 for the 'stride' that was shortened; his walk that was once vigorous now carries him captive to death. The irony is structural."
