          "body": "Verse 21 closes the speech with a generalizing maxim that functions as a verdict: 'Surely such are the dwellings of the wicked, and this is the place of him who does not know God.' The word translated 'does not know God' (*lo yada el*) is devastating in its implication — not merely intellectual ignorance but relational alienation, the covenantal estrangement that the Old Testament consistently presents as the root of moral disaster (cf. Jeremiah 22:16: 'To know Me is to do justice'). Applied to Job, it is the cruelest charge yet leveled by any of the friends. But the book's frame ensures the reader knows it is false: 'there is no one like him on the earth, a blameless and upright man, fearing God and turning away from evil' (1:8). God Himself provides the counter-testimony before a single friend speaks. Bildad's closing maxim is true in the abstract — the wicked do not know God, and their end is ruin. Calvin noted that the friends 'mingled many truths with their errors, which gave their falsehood the appearance of wisdom.' But the maxim is catastrophically misapplied. Job 42:7-9 is the book's decisive commentary on Job 18:21: the LORD says to Eliphaz, 'You have not spoken of Me what is right, as My servant Job has.' The same Job whom Bildad has just described as the man who does not know God is the man whose speech God endorses and whose intercession the friends require."
